   =20
      Bad margin loan
   =20
 =20

I don=E2=80=99t know, here=E2=80=99s a trade:
=09You go to a bank and say =E2=80=9CI would like to buy $1 billion of bond=
s, but I don=E2=80=99t have $1 billion. Why don=E2=80=99t you lend me the $=
1 billion, and I=E2=80=99ll buy the bonds, and you can take the bonds as co=
llateral.=E2=80=9D=09The bank is like =E2=80=9Cwell okay how much of your o=
wn money are you proposing to put up?=E2=80=9D=09You are like =E2=80=9Cuh I=
=E2=80=99ve got like $200 in my checking account, but that=E2=80=99s not th=
e point. The point is that you=E2=80=99ll have the bonds as collateral, so =
it=E2=80=99s fine.=E2=80=9D=09The bank is like =E2=80=9Csure I guess, here=
=E2=80=99s $1 billion.=E2=80=9D=09You buy the bonds, the market moves again=
st you, the bank=E2=80=99s collateral loses $100 million of value, the bank=
 comes to you and says =E2=80=9Chey you owe us the $100 million,=E2=80=9D a=
nd you are like =E2=80=9Cwell, like I said, I=E2=80=99ve got $200, you can =
have that.=E2=80=9D

Is that a trade? Does that happen? It seems implausible. Normally banks req=
uire more margin than that: They won=E2=80=99t lend you $1 billion against =
a $1 billion bond portfolio; they=E2=80=99ll lend you, like, $500 million o=
r $800 million or something, demanding that you put up some equity to insul=
ate them from losses.=C2=A0Still there are exceptions, though not at the li=
teral =E2=80=9C$200 in my checking account=E2=80=9D level. Is the  story of=
  Archegos=C2=A0something like this? Banks loaned Bill Hwang=E2=80=99s fami=
ly office billions of dollars, secured by stock positions, with relatively =
little equity, and then lost billions when those stocks went down.
Anyway here=E2=80=99s a very weird story by  Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Harry=
 Wilson, Donal Griffin=C2=A0and Jonathan Browning:

The founders of a failed London brokerage, which saddled some of the world=
=E2=80=99s largest banks with tens of millions of dollars of trading losses=
 when it collapsed, have settled a $125 million lawsuit for pennies on the =
dollar.
Alberto Statti and Caterina De=E2=80=99Medici =E2=80=94 who set up Invexsta=
r Capital Management =E2=80=94 agreed to pay the firm=E2=80=99s liquidators=
 =E2=82=AC500,000 ($541,000) to settle a legal claim against them after =E2=
=80=9Cprotracted correspondence,=E2=80=9D according to a UK corporate filin=
g. The pair have paid =E2=82=AC350,000 so far and =E2=80=9Cdiscussions=E2=
=80=9D are ongoing about the rest, the filing shows.
At the time of its collapse eight years ago, Invexstar had built up trading=
 positions with a notional value of more than =C2=A31.25 billion ($1.59 bil=
lion) despite having capital of less than =C2=A31 million. Wall Street bank=
s including BNP Paribas SA, Morgan Stanley and Nomura Holdings Inc., were l=
eft nursing more than =C2=A3100 million of losses when Invexstar was forced=
 to close after the firm was caught out by moves in the bond market.

=E2=80=9CCapital of less than=C2=A0=C2=A31 million=E2=80=9D is not quite =
=E2=80=9C$200 in my checking account,=E2=80=9D but it=E2=80=99s pretty clos=
e! It=E2=80=99s closer to that than it is to Archegos. And if you give some=
one 1,250x leverage you are going to be=C2=A0lucky=C2=A0to get back pennies=
 on the dollar. In fact, these banks didn=E2=80=99t;=C2=A0=E2=82=AC500,000 =
on a=C2=A0$125 million claim is like half a penny on the dollar.

 =20
   =20
      Grayscale premia
   =20
 =20

A lot of people, it turns out, want exposure to crypto prices without expos=
ure to crypto=C2=A0infrastructure. Like: Bitcoin was created as sort of an =
alternative financial infrastructure, a new kind of money that dispenses wi=
th the need for banks and other intermediaries. But in fact Bitcoin is not =
a particularly good form of money (its value is volatile, it is not widely =
used for payments in a lot of places), but it is a very good sort of financ=
ial asset (its value has gone up a lot over the last 14 years, and also rec=
ently). So a lot of people want to=C2=A0own Bitcoin=C2=A0(because they thin=
k the price will go up) without believing in, or caring about, its underlyi=
ng philosophy of decentralization and disintermediation. So they go to thei=
r (traditional) bank or (traditional) brokerage and say =E2=80=9Cbuy me som=
e Bitcoin.=E2=80=9D
And there are lots of products designed to satisfy that desire: Bitcoin fut=
ures and, soon, probably,  spot Bitcoin exchange-traded funds that let you =
buy exposure to Bitcoin=C2=A0without ever leaving the traditional financial=
 system. Someone else will do the arbitrage for you, buying Bitcoins to sel=
l you Bitcoin futures or ETFs, and you=E2=80=99ll just have a thing in your=
 regular brokerage account that moves up and down with the price of Bitcoin=
.
I have  written about this  before and it seems fine to me? If the=C2=A0onl=
y=C2=A0possible thesis for buying Bitcoin was =E2=80=9Cthis is the future o=
f money and the entire traditional financial system will be replaced by cry=
pto,=E2=80=9D then buying Bitcoin in an ETF would be a little contradictory=
. But in the actual world of 2023 it=E2=80=99s fine.
I don=E2=80=99t really get the case for a Filecoin ETF? The Financial Times=
 reports:

Some cryptocurrency funds run by the world=E2=80=99s largest crypto manager=
 are trading at as much as eight times their underlying value amid an unpre=
cedented buying frenzy. ...
The mania has spread to a host of private trusts operated by Grayscale. The=
 company=E2=80=99s Filecoin Trust is trading at $34.25, 721 per cent above =
its net asset value of $4.17, having hit a premium of more than 1,000 per c=
ent in November.
Its trust tracking solana, the third-largest cryptocurrency after bitcoin a=
nd ether, is at a premium of 302 per cent, while those investing in chainli=
nk, livepeer, lumens and Decentraland=E2=80=99s mana token are priced at be=
tween twice and four times their NAV.
=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s absurd. I feel the investor doesn=E2=80=99t really un=
derstand what they are getting into,=E2=80=9D said Bradley Duke, chief stra=
tegist of ETC Group, which runs more than $1bn in European-listed crypto ex=
change traded products.
=E2=80=9CI wouldn=E2=80=99t know what [investors] could be thinking buying =
at these prices,=E2=80=9D said Bryan Armour, director of passive strategies=
 research, North America, at Morningstar. =E2=80=9CA lack of understanding =
can easily be part of it.=E2=80=9D
The funds can only be traded via the over-the-counter =E2=80=9Cpink sheets=
=E2=80=9D market, where secondary trading in pre-existing shares takes plac=
e. Shares cannot be redeemed, while new shares can only be created if Grays=
cale carries out a private placement exercise, meaning there is no arbitrag=
e mechanism to bring prices back in line with the underlying holdings.

To be clear, these Grayscale trusts are=C2=A0not=C2=A0ETFs, because you can=
=E2=80=99t create or redeem them; if they were ETFs they probably wouldn=E2=
=80=99t trade at those crazy premiums. (You=E2=80=99d go buy a ton of Filec=
oins and give them to Grayscale to get back trust shares, etc.) But Graysca=
le=E2=80=99s biggest trust is the one tracking Bitcoin; it has traded at a =
discount for a long time, but that discount has closed significantly now th=
at everyone expects the trust to convert into an ETF (and thus allow redemp=
tions). That optimism has been good for the price of Bitcoin too, and for t=
he prices of crypto generally, and also apparently for the prices of Graysc=
ale altcoin trusts.=C2=A0
Bitcoin is a popular financial asset, =E2=80=9Cdigital gold,=E2=80=9D a pos=
sible diversifier for retail and institutional investors. Filecoin is =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0the payment currency for a  peer-to-peer file storage system? W=
hy would you buy it in a pink-sheet wrapper? The Grayscale Filecoin Trust i=
s tiny (half a million dollars under management), but owning Filecoin that =
way is (1) less useful and (2) vastly more expensive than owning it directl=
y.=C2=A0
One possible answer is of course =E2=80=9Ca lack of understanding=E2=80=9D;=
 again, this stuff is very small. I suppose another answer is, like, =E2=80=
=9Ccrypto projects like Filecoin are good and valuable, and their tokens ar=
e sort of like stock in those projects, but the=C2=A0stock exchange for tra=
ding those stocks=C2=A0will be the regular stock exchange, not decentralize=
d finance.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Last year it was almost plausible to think that th=
e crypto financial system might consume the regular financial system, that =
in the future all the stocks will be tokenized. Now it=E2=80=99s more plaus=
ible to think the reverse, that the regular financial system will consume t=
he crypto one, that in the future all tokens will be stock-ized.

